NOTES_MICAH = {
    1: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Micah the Morashtite was from Moresheth-gath (cf. v.14), a town in the Shephelah region of Judah, southwest of Jerusalem. His ministry spanned the reigns of Jotham (750-735 BC), Ahaz (735-715 BC), and Hezekiah (715-686 BC), making him a contemporary of Isaiah and Hosea. His prophetic vision (chazah, H2372) encompasses both the northern capital Samaria and the southern capital Jerusalem, framing a message of universal judgment.',
        2: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The call "Hear, O peoples" (shim\'u ammim, H8085/H5971) invokes a cosmic courtroom scene in which YHWH serves as witness (ed, H5707) against the nations. The phrase "my Lord YHWH" uses Adonai (H136) alongside the Tetragrammaton. The "holy temple" (hekal qodsho) may refer simultaneously to the earthly Jerusalem sanctuary and the heavenly divine council chamber, paralleling Psalm 82:1 and Isaiah 6:1. (Ps 82:1, Isa 6:1)',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s "coming out from his place" (yatza mimqomo, H3318/H4725) is a theophanic descent formula, denoting divine abandonment of his sanctuary and the onset of judgment. The trampling of the "high places" (bamot, H1116) is doubly significant: bamot were literal Canaanite cultic sites adopted by Israel, and their destruction signals YHWH\'s reclamation of creation\'s high places from false worship. TYPOLOGY: This theophanic imagery anticipates the final descent of YHWH in Revelation 19. (Deut 32:13, Amos 4:13, Rev 19:11-15)',
        5: 'HEBREW: "Transgression" (pesha, H6588) carries the sense of deliberate rebellion or breach of covenant, stronger than mere inadvertent sin (chata, H2398). By identifying Samaria and Jerusalem as the embodiment of Israel\'s and Judah\'s sin respectively, Micah indicts the capitals and their sanctioned worship systems — the political and religious elite — rather than the rural poor. This rhetorical structure is characteristic of Micah\'s social critique. (Amos 3:9-10, Mic 3:1-4)',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "wages of prostitution" (etnan zonah, H868/H2181) likely refers to the wealth accumulated through syncretistic temple prostitution and idolatrous trade at Samaria\'s cult sites. The irony of the verse is deliberate: wealth gained for idol-worship will be recycled as spoils for the conquering nation\'s own idols. Micah here echoes Hosea\'s metaphor of Israel as an adulterous wife. (Hos 2:12, Deut 23:18)',
        9: 'HEBREW: "Incurable" (anush, H605) is the same root used in Jeremiah 17:9 for the deceitful heart ("desperately sick"). The wound (makah, H4347) that began in Samaria has now metastasized to reach Judah\'s own gate. This verse serves as the theological hinge of the chapter: the judgment is not contained but spreads southward, reaching Jerusalem itself. (Jer 17:9, Isa 1:5-6)',
        10: 'HEBREW: Verse 10 opens with an allusion to David\'s lament: "Tell it not in Gath" (al-tagidu b\'Gath) echoes 2 Samuel 1:20, invoking the memory of national catastrophe. Micah then employs an extended series of wordplays (paronomasia) through verses 10-15, matching the town names with their fates — a literary device with roots in prophetic lament poetry. "Beth-le-aphrah" means "house of dust," making the command to "roll in dust" a bitter pun on the city\'s own name. (2 Sam 1:20)',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: Lachish was the second most important city in Judah, a major military and administrative center in the Shephelah. Archaeological excavations have confirmed its destruction by Sennacherib in 701 BC, corroborating the prophetic context. Micah\'s accusation that Lachish was the "beginning of sin" (reshit chat\'at, H7225/H2403) to Zion may indicate that northern Israelite idolatrous practices entered Judah via Lachish\'s trade routes. (2 Kgs 18:14, Isa 36:2)',
        15: 'TYPOLOGY: "The glory of Israel shall come to Adullam" is a cryptic but powerful statement. Adullam was the cave where David and his mighty men — the rejected and dispossessed — gathered (1 Sam 22:1). Micah may be anticipating the humiliation of the Judean elite, driven like David\'s outcasts to caves. On a deeper typological level, this foreshadows the Son of David who, rejected, gathers the broken and dispossessed around himself before his ultimate vindication. (1 Sam 22:1-2, Matt 5:3-5)',
        16: 'HEBREW: Shaving the head bald (qorcha, H7144) and cutting the hair were ancient Near Eastern signs of extreme mourning, normally prohibited for Israelites in certain contexts (Deut 14:1) but invoked here as an intensified lament. The comparison to the "eagle" (nesher, H5404) — likely the griffon vulture, whose bald head was a recognized image — heightens the grimness of the exile imagery. "Children of your delight" (bene ta\'anugayikh) are the beloved children carried into Assyrian captivity. (Deut 14:1, Amos 8:10, 2 Kgs 17:6)',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Devise iniquity" (חָשַׁב אָוֶן, hashav aven; Strong\'s H2803, H205) — the verb hashav ("to think, plan, devise") is the same root used of skilled craftsmen and of divine wisdom, here grotesquely inverted. The phrase "upon their beds" emphasizes premeditated sin; the wicked scheme through the night and execute at dawn. This mirrors the covenantal curses of Leviticus 26 falling upon covenant-breakers.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s response mirrors the crime precisely — the oppressors "devised" (hashav) evil; now YHWH "devises" (hashav) calamity against them. This is the lex talionis operating at a covenantal level. The "family" (mishpachah) indicted may refer to the ruling house or the nation corporately as a covenant household.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Taunt-song" (מָשָׁל, mashal; Strong\'s H4912) denotes a proverb, parable, or mocking byword. The Hebrew of this verse is notoriously compressed and difficult; the shift between speakers mid-verse is intentional, dramatizing the chaos of judgment. "He allots our fields to the apostate" (שׁוֹבֵב, shovev) depicts YHWH reassigning the stolen land to those who turned away — a bitter reversal for those who hoarded property.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The question "Is the Spirit (ruach) of YHWH impatient?" challenges the false comfort of those who presume YHWH will not act in judgment. The Hebrew ruach (Strong\'s H7307) — spirit, wind, breath — is the animating presence and power of YHWH. The rhetorical questions expose a theology of presumption: the people have domesticated YHWH into a deity who only blesses. Compare Isaiah 63:10 where Israel "grieved his Holy Spirit."',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: The eviction of women from their homes reflects the brutal social consequences of debt foreclosure and land-seizure in 8th-century Judah. Deuteronomy 14–15 and Leviticus 25 established jubilee and debt-release laws to prevent exactly this accumulation of property among elites. Archaeological evidence from the period confirms a sharp stratification of wealth in Iron Age IIB Judah.',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: This sudden oracle of restoration (vv. 12–13) is unexpected after sustained judgment, modeling the pattern of Micah\'s entire book: doom followed by hope. The "remnant" (שְׁאֵרִית, she\'erit; Strong\'s H7611) is a key Micah theme (cf. Mic 4:7; 5:7–8; 7:18). The gathering of scattered Israel anticipates the ingathering of the nations under Messiah (cf. John 10:16; Eph 2:11–22). "Bozrah" may evoke the imagery of a royal sheepfold and later appears in eschatological contexts (Isa 63:1).',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: "The one who breaks open" (הַפֹּרֵץ, ha-poretz; Strong\'s H6555) is a title — the Breaker — whose identity is debated but ultimately finds its fullest meaning in the Messiah who bursts the gates of death and leads his people out (cf. John 10:3–4; Rev 19:11–16). The sequence — Breaker leads, king goes before, YHWH at the head — is a divine warrior procession. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The image of YHWH "at their head" (בְּרֹאשָׁם) as divine warrior-king heading a triumphant procession echoes ancient Near Eastern conquest theology where the national deity marches at the vanguard of his people\'s armies, decisively reclaiming territory from rival powers.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The chapter opens with the particle "wa\'omar" (and I said), placing Micah himself as the speaker — a rare first-person intrusion that asserts prophetic authority. "Mishpat" (H4941, justice/judgment) is the governing concern of the entire oracle; it denotes not merely fairness but the administration of covenantal order as YHWH defines it. The address to "heads" (ro\'shim) and "rulers" (qetsinim) indicts the civil leadership specifically, not the general populace.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The cannibal-butcher imagery draws on an ancient Near Eastern curse-language for oppression. In its deepest typological register, the rulers who devour the flesh of God\'s people stand in stark contrast to the Good Shepherd of Ezekiel 34 and John 10 — a contrast Micah himself prepares for in chapter 5 with the ruler from Bethlehem. The brutality described here anticipates the NT condemnation of shepherds who exploit the flock (John 10:12-13).',
        5: 'HEBREW: "Shalom" (H7965) here is spoken falsely — a biting irony, as the word that denotes wholeness and covenantal well-being is weaponized by false prophets for personal gain. "Consecrate war" (qidshu milhamah) is a technical cultic term for declaring holy war, here grotesquely turned against those who do not pay the prophet\'s fee. THEOLOGICAL: This verse exposes the commodification of prophecy — the sin of preaching what congregants pay to hear rather than what YHWH commands.',
        7: 'HISTORICAL: In ancient Israel and the broader ANE, prophets and diviners held public roles as mediators of divine speech. "Covering the lips" (atu al-saphim) was a gesture of mourning and public shame (cf. Lev 13:45; Ezek 24:17). The silence of false prophets at the moment of crisis contrasts directly with Micah\'s boldness in verse 8, structuring the passage as an antithesis between counterfeit and authentic prophetic ministry.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Verse 8 is the theological center of the chapter — a stunning contrast to the venal prophets of verses 5-7. Micah attributes his prophetic power not to skill or status but to the "ruach" (H7307, Spirit/wind/breath) of YHWH. This is one of the clearest OT affirmations of Spirit-empowered prophetic ministry, anticipating the NT gift of the Spirit poured out for proclamation (Acts 2:17-18). The triad of "power, justice, and might" defines authentic prophetic character.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: Verse 11 identifies the deepest corruption: these leaders invoke YHWH\'s name and presence as a talisman against judgment while simultaneously violating every covenantal obligation. This is a form of presumption theology — reducing YHWH to a protective deity whose presence guarantees national security regardless of ethical conduct. Jesus confronts the same logic in Matthew 7:22-23. HISTORICAL: The hiring of priests and prophets for payment reflects the patronage economy of ancient Israelite cult institutions.',
        12: 'HISTORICAL: Verse 12 is quoted verbatim by the elders in Jeremiah 26:18 as legal precedent for prophetic free speech — the only OT instance where a prophet is explicitly cited by name to justify another prophet\'s oracle against Jerusalem. This establishes Micah 3:12 as foundational for the theology of prophetic accountability. The fulfilled threat of Jerusalem\'s destruction (587 BC) and the temple mount becoming overgrown validates Micah\'s words. TYPOLOGY: The plowing of Zion anticipates both the Roman destruction of Jerusalem (70 AD) and the eschatological renewal of Zion in Micah 4:1-2.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'TYPOLOGY: The phrase "latter days" (Hebrew: acharit hayamim, H319) is a technical eschatological marker in the prophets, pointing to a future age of Messianic fulfillment. This verse is nearly identical to Isaiah 2:2, suggesting a shared oracle or liturgical tradition. The exaltation of YHWH\'s mountain over all others is a direct counter to the divine council cosmology of the ANE, where gods were associated with cosmic mountains (cf. Ps 48:2; Isa 14:13). The NT understands the "mountain of YHWH\'s house" as realized in the Messianic community gathered to the risen Christ (Heb 12:22).',
        2: 'HEBREW: "Instruction" here is torah (H8451), not merely "law" in the legal sense, but divine teaching and direction proceeding from God\'s own character. Its going forth from Zion reverses the Babel-pattern of human striving and replaces it with centripetal divine initiative — the nations come to YHWH rather than building their own tower. THEOLOGICAL: The universality of this verse is striking; the same torah given to Israel becomes the pathway for all nations. This anticipates the Great Commission and the Pentecost ingathering (Acts 2).',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The beating of swords into plowshares is the definitive image of Messianic shalom (peace/wholeness). Joel 3:10 reverses this image for the day of battle, showing these oracles are eschatologically framed. The cessation of war "learning" implies a deep anthropological transformation — war as a practice must be unlearned, pointing to the renewal of the human heart. NT fulfillment: Christ is described as our peace (shalom) who has broken down the dividing wall (Eph 2:14-17).',
        4: 'HISTORICAL: "Each man under his vine and under his fig tree" (cf. 1 Kgs 4:25; Zech 3:10) is a well-attested image of royal prosperity and covenant blessing in ancient Israel and the ANE. It evokes Solomon\'s reign as a type of the coming Messianic kingdom\'s security and abundance. The phrase "none shall make them afraid" echoes the covenant blessing of Leviticus 26:6, signaling full covenantal restoration.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The assertion that "YHWH will reign over them in Mount Zion from this time forth and forevermore" is a bold declaration of YHWH\'s direct and everlasting kingship. This stands against both the immediate political crisis and the cosmic backdrop of rival divine claims. The remnant (she\'erit, H7611) theology is central to Micah: judgment does not mean annihilation but a purified, restored community (cf. Mic 5:7-8; Rom 9:27).',
        8: 'HEBREW: "Migdal-eder" (H4029, tower of the flock) appears also in Genesis 35:21 near Bethlehem, where Jacob camped after Rachel\'s death. Early Jewish tradition (Targum Pseudo-Jonathan on Gen 35:21) connects this location with the future revelation of the Messiah-King. TYPOLOGY: The proximity of this Bethlehem-adjacent term to the Messianic birth oracle of Micah 5:2 is theologically significant and was likely understood messianically by Second Temple readers.',
        10: 'HISTORICAL: The mention of Babylon by name is remarkable and debated. Micah prophesied in the late 8th century BC, when Assyria was the dominant threat — Babylon\'s rise to supremacy came later. Some scholars see this as genuine predictive prophecy; others posit later editorial activity. THEOLOGICAL: Regardless, the structure of the oracle is clear: captivity is not the end. YHWH promises both the exile (judgment) and the redemption from it, establishing his sovereign control over both movements of history (cf. Jer 29:10-14).',
        12: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The phrase "thoughts of YHWH" (machshevot YHWH, H4284) contrasts the limited perspective of the nations with YHWH\'s sovereign hidden counsel. This is a wisdom-warfare motif: the nations assemble thinking themselves conquerors, but they are unwitting instruments in YHWH\'s harvesting judgment. The image of gathering as sheaves to a threshing floor appears also in divine warfare contexts (Jer 51:33; Rev 14:14-20), where YHWH is the divine harvester.',
        13: 'HEBREW: "Horn" (qeren, H7161) is a standard Hebrew metaphor for power and strength, often used of kings and nations (Deut 33:17; Ps 75:10; Dan 7-8). "Devote" (hacharam, H2763) is the language of the cherem — sacred destruction devoted entirely to YHWH, as in holy war. THEOLOGICAL: The concluding declaration "Lord of all the earth" (adon kol-ha\'arets) is a title used at liminal moments of YHWH\'s cosmic assertion of sovereignty (Josh 3:11, 13; Zech 4:14; 6:5), affirming that Israel\'s victory is ultimately a declaration of YHWH\'s universal reign.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: The opening verse (numbered v. 1 in English; v. 4:14 in Hebrew) addresses Jerusalem as "daughter of troops" under siege — likely the Assyrian assault of Sennacherib (701 BC) or, proleptically, the Babylonian siege. The striking of the judge on the cheek is a gesture of profound humiliation in ANE legal culture, echoing the mockery of Israel\'s royal leadership. TYPOLOGY: The struck judge anticipates the Servant who is struck and shamed (Isa 50:6), fulfilled in the striking of Jesus before the Sanhedrin (Matt 26:67).',
        2: 'HEBREW: "\'Alphey" (Strong\'s H504) means "clans" or "thousands," indicating Bethlehem\'s insignificance in tribal mustering lists. "Moshel" (H4910) denotes a ruler or one who governs with authority. "\'Olam" (H5769) carries the sense of antiquity stretching to the horizon of time — "ancient days" or "eternity," pointing to the pre-existence of the coming ruler. TYPOLOGY: This is the most direct messianic prophecy in Micah, cited verbatim in Matt 2:6 and alluded to in John 7:42. The Bethlehem origin combined with eternal "goings forth" (motsa\'otav) forms the tension between incarnate humanity and divine pre-existence resolved only in the person of Jesus the Messiah (John 1:1-14; Col 1:17).',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: "She who is in labor" likely carries a double reference — to Israel\'s travail under exile and, typologically, to the birth of the Messiah himself (cf. Isa 7:14; 66:7-8; Rev 12:1-5). The giving up of Israel until the birth signals a redemptive-historical interval between promise and fulfillment. The "rest of his brothers" returning echoes the regathering theme central to the new exodus hope.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The shepherd-king imagery unites the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7) with the divine warrior who stands to rule. Ruling "in the strength of YHWH" and "in the majesty (ga\'on) of the name of YHWH his God" affirms that the Messiah\'s authority is derived from and subordinate to YHWH, yet he himself bears that name before the nations. TYPOLOGY: Jesus as the Good Shepherd who rules to the ends of the earth fulfills this portrait (John 10:11; Phil 2:9-11).',
        5: 'HEBREW: "Shalom" (H7965) here functions as a title or predicate — "this one shall be peace (shalom)" — not merely a state of peace but the Messiah himself as the embodiment and agent of shalom. THEOLOGICAL: The Assyrian represents the archetypal imperial enemy, and the seven shepherds and eight princes is a wisdom formula (cf. Eccl 11:2) signifying complete, overflowing provision of leadership. TYPOLOGY: Christ as "our peace" (Eph 2:14) who breaks down the dividing wall is the ultimate fulfillment of this peace-bringer language.',
        7: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The remnant\'s blessing is described as coming "like dew from YHWH" — dew in the ANE was understood as a direct divine gift not subject to human agency or natural mechanisms controlled by Baal (cf. Hos 14:5; Deut 33:28). This passage asserts YHWH\'s exclusive sovereignty over blessing, undercutting rival divine patrons of fertility. THEOLOGICAL: The remnant\'s role among the nations is passive and gracious — a channel of divine blessing — contrasting with the active, conquering image of v. 8, revealing the two-sided nature of Israel\'s missional presence.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The lion imagery draws on the Judahite royal tradition (Gen 49:9) where Judah/the Davidic king is the lion among nations. The remnant here takes on royal and militant characteristics, suggesting that the scattered community participates in the Messiah\'s ultimate triumph over hostile nations. This tension between dew (v. 7) and lion (v. 8) reflects the dual aspects of the coming kingdom: grace and judgment.',
        12: 'HEBREW: "Keshaphim" (H3785) refers to sorceries or witchcraft, derived from the root kashaph. "\'Oveney" (H6049) denotes those who practice divination or observe omens, a class of practitioners condemned throughout the Torah (Deut 18:10-12). THEOLOGICAL: The purging of occult practices is integral to the coming redemption — the removal of false spiritual intermediaries makes way for direct access to YHWH, fulfilled ultimately in Christ who renders all mediatory magic obsolete (Acts 8:9-24; Rev 21:8).',
        13: 'HEBREW: "Pesilim" (H6456) are carved or graven images, from the root pasal, to carve or hew. "Matstsevot" (H4676) are standing stones or sacred pillars, often associated with Canaanite high-place worship and ancestral cult veneration. HISTORICAL: Archaeological evidence from sites such as Arad and Megiddo confirms the prevalence of standing stones in Israelite worship contexts, reflecting the persistent syncretism Micah condemns.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "\'Asherim" (H842) are wooden poles or stylized trees representing the Canaanite goddess Asherah, consort of El in the Ugaritic divine council tradition. Their uprooting is a polemic against the rival divine feminine figure who had penetrated even official Yahwistic worship (cf. 2 Kgs 21:7; 23:6). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The systematic removal of Asherah poles, carved images, and pillars signals YHWH\'s reclamation of sole divine prerogative over Israel, dismantling the structures through which territorial and household deities were invoked (Deut 32:17; Ps 82).',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The concluding verse grounds the purification of Israel and the judgment of nations in YHWH\'s "anger and wrath" (\'aph and chemah) — covenantal terms for divine response to persistent rebellion. The nations that "have not obeyed" signals that the nations bear moral accountability to YHWH as Creator and cosmic sovereign, not merely to their own patron deities. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This accountability implies YHWH\'s supreme authority over all nations even where other divine beings have been allotted oversight (Deut 32:8-9), anticipating the final reclamation declared in Ps 82:8.',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'STRUCTURE: Micah 6 opens a covenant lawsuit (rib pattern) in which YHWH summons the mountains and foundations of the earth as witnesses — a motif rooted in Deut 32:1 where heaven and earth are called as witnesses to the Mosaic covenant. The call to "arise and contend" (qum riv) signals a formal legal proceeding in the divine court. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The mountains and "enduring foundations" (mosdei arets) may reflect the cosmic witnesses of the heavenly assembly, consistent with Deut 32 geography of nations. (Deut 32:1; Ps 82:1; Isa 1:2)',
        2: 'HEBREW: The word "controversy" (riv, Strong\'s H7379) denotes a legal dispute or lawsuit. Its repeated use in vv. 1-2 establishes the formal juridical tone of the entire chapter. THEOLOGICAL: YHWH as plaintiff against His own covenant people mirrors the structure of Hittite suzerainty treaties, where the great king could indict a vassal for covenant violation. The "enduring foundations" serve as eternal, impartial witnesses. (Isa 1:2; Deut 32:1; Hos 4:1)',
        4: 'HISTORICAL: The mention of Moses, Aaron, and Miriam as a triad of leaders is unique in the OT — only here are all three named together as co-leaders of the Exodus. This reflects ancient tradition of Miriam\'s prophetic leadership (Exod 15:20). YHWH\'s recounting of redemptive acts is a standard element of the covenant lawsuit, rehearsing the basis of the relationship. (Exod 15:20; Num 20:1; Ps 77:20)',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: The Balaam episode (Num 22-24) and the journey from Shittim (the last encampment in Moab) to Gilgal (the first encampment in Canaan) summarize the entire wilderness-to-conquest transition. HEBREW: "Righteous acts" (tsidqot, Strong\'s H6666, plural of tsedaqah) refers to YHWH\'s saving deeds of covenant faithfulness — His acts of vindication on behalf of His people. TYPOLOGY: The crossing from Shittim to Gilgal foreshadows the ultimate crossing from bondage to inheritance, fulfilled in Christ\'s redemption. (Num 22-24; Josh 4:19; Rom 5:8)',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Micah 6:8 stands as one of the great ethical summaries of the entire OT, distilling the prophetic demand into three interlocking imperatives: doing justice (mishpat, Strong\'s H4941), loving covenant-loyalty (hesed, Strong\'s H2617), and humble walking (tsana halak) with God. HEBREW: "Humbly" (tsanea, Strong\'s H6800) occurs only here in the OT — it implies not meekness alone but a careful, attentive walk of dependence. TYPOLOGY: Jesus embodied all three perfectly (Matt 12:18-20; John 13:1-17; Phil 2:8) and fulfills the prophetic ethic from within. (Deut 10:12; Hos 6:6; Matt 23:23; Phil 2:8)',
        9: 'HEBREW: The phrase "it is wisdom to fear Your name" (tushiyyah yirah shemecha) is textually difficult — "tushiyyah" (Strong\'s H8454) denotes practical wisdom or sound counsel. Some manuscripts read this as a parenthetical note affirming that fearing YHWH\'s name is itself wisdom. THEOLOGICAL: The unnamed "tribe" and the one who has "appointed" the coming judgment signal both communal accountability and YHWH\'s sovereign orchestration of discipline. (Prov 1:7; Isa 28:29)',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "I also have made you sick in striking you" uses a causative construction emphasizing YHWH\'s direct agency in covenant curse. This recalls the curse formulas of Leviticus 26 and Deuteronomy 28, where illness, military defeat, and agricultural failure are covenantal consequences. HEBREW: The Hebrew lehakotka (to strike you) reflects the verb nakah (Strong\'s H5221), used of divine judgment blows throughout the prophets. (Lev 26:16; Deut 28:22; Amos 4:9)',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The pattern of "sow but not reap / tread but not use" reflects the classic covenant curse of futility (Deut 28:38-40), where labor yields no fruit. This is the reversal of the creation and Promised Land blessing. TYPOLOGY: The ultimate inversion of these curses comes in Christ, who bore covenant curse so that the redeemed inherit an unending harvest. (Deut 28:38-40; Amos 5:11; Gal 3:13; Rev 22:2)',
        16: 'HISTORICAL: Omri and Ahab represent the apex of northern royal apostasy — Omri founded Samaria and introduced systematic state idolatry, while Ahab expanded it through Baal worship (1 Kgs 16:25-33). That Judah is now accused of following Omri\'s statutes is a severe indictment, collapsing the distinction between the two kingdoms in terms of covenant unfaithfulness. THEOLOGICAL: "A hissing" (sheruqah, Strong\'s H8322) denotes the shuddering contempt of horrified passersby — the exact opposite of the honor YHWH intended for His people among the nations. (1 Kgs 16:25-33; Jer 18:16; Deut 28:37)',
    },
    7: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The opening "Allelai li" (woe is me) echoes lament psalms. The imagery of gleaning after harvest (Strong\'s H5955, \'oleloth) pictures a land morally stripped bare. The "first-ripe fig" (bikkurah, H1063) was a delicacy, signifying what is most desirable — Micah mourns its absence in human society. Compare Jeremiah\'s similar lament (Jer 5:1).',
        2: 'HEBREW: "Hasid" (H2623) denotes the one characterized by hesed — covenantal loyalty and faithfulness — here declared extinct. The hunting imagery with a "net" (herem, H2764) pictures predatory social relations, the strong ensnaring the weak. THEOLOGICAL: The complete moral collapse described here recalls the conditions of Noah\'s day (Gen 6:5) and anticipates eschatological lawlessness (2 Tim 3:2-4).',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes this verse nearly verbatim in Matthew 10:35-36 and Luke 12:53, applying it to the divisions His own coming would provoke within households. The citation indicates Micah\'s words had an eschatological horizon: the upheaval of the end-time visitation begins in the ministry of the Messiah. THEOLOGICAL: Family loyalty, the foundation of ancient Israelite social order, collapses under comprehensive covenant infidelity.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "I will watch expectantly" (tsaphah, H6822) is a sentinel term — the prophet takes up his post as a watchman waiting for divine response. "The God of my salvation" (yeshu\'ati, from yeshua, H3444) anticipates the very name of Jesus (Yeshua). THEOLOGICAL: Verse 7 is the pivotal turn of the chapter from communal lament to individual trust, structurally identical to the "turn" in many lament psalms (cf. Ps 13:5-6).',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The speaker\'s willing acceptance of divine discipline ("the wrath of YHWH I will bear — because I have sinned") models genuine penitential theology. "Tsedaqah" (H6666, righteousness) here denotes YHWH\'s covenant-faithful vindication of the one who waits. TYPOLOGY: The movement from bearing wrath, to being brought into light, to beholding righteousness, prefigures the substitutionary and justifying work of the Messiah on behalf of sinners (Isa 53; Rom 3:26).',
        14: 'HEBREW: "Shebet" (H7626) is both "staff" and "tribe," evoking the shepherd-king imagery central to Davidic messianism. "Who dwell alone" (badad, H910) alludes to Balaam\'s oracle (Num 23:9), Israel\'s peculiar separated status among the nations. THEOLOGICAL: The prayer for Bashan and Gilead — territories lost to Assyrian conquest — expresses hope for full territorial restoration under the coming Shepherd-King (Ezek 34:23-24; John 10:11).',
        15: 'TYPOLOGY: The Exodus functions as the paradigmatic act of divine redemption throughout the prophets; here a new, greater Exodus is anticipated. "Niphlaoth" (H6381, wonders, marvels) is the vocabulary of the Exodus plagues and the Red Sea crossing (Exod 15:11). The NT presents the ministry, death, and resurrection of Yeshua as precisely this new Exodus (Luke 9:31; 1 Cor 10:1-4).',
        17: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The prostration of the nations before YHWH — licking dust like serpents, trembling from strongholds — describes the final subjugation of the powers that had lorded over the nations (cf. Deut 32:8; Ps 82:8). The serpent imagery (nachash) may deliberately evoke the primal enemy of Genesis 3:14, whose defeat is here extended cosmically. THEOLOGICAL: "They shall turn in dread to YHWH our God" implies a coerced rather than voluntary submission, distinguishing it from the willing worship of the redeemed remnant.',
        18: 'HEBREW: "Who is a God like You?" (Mi-El kamocha) is a direct wordplay on the prophet\'s own name — Micah (Mikayahu) means "Who is like YHWH?" The entire book thus culminates in the answer to its own author\'s name. "Pardoning iniquity" (nose\' avon, H5375/H5771) literally means "lifting/carrying iniquity," a term used of the scapegoat (Lev 16:22) and the Suffering Servant (Isa 53:12). TYPOLOGY: This verse is the theological summit of the book and a direct anticipation of the atoning work of Messiah Yeshua.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Cast all their sins into the depths of the sea" (metsuloth yam) is among the most vivid images of total divine forgiveness in all of Scripture — sins not merely covered but removed to an unretrievable depth. TYPOLOGY: The casting into the sea recalls the destruction of Egypt\'s army at the Red Sea (Exod 15:5, 10), making forgiveness a new Exodus event. This verse grounds the NT\'s proclamation of total forgiveness in Messiah (Col 2:13-14; Heb 10:17).',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The chapter closes by anchoring divine mercy in the sworn covenants to Abraham and the patriarchs — "emet" (H571, truth/faithfulness) to Jacob and "hesed" (H2617, steadfast covenantal love) to Abraham. This covenantal foundation is precisely what Paul cites in Romans 15:8-9 to explain the inclusion of both Jews and Gentiles in Messiah. TYPOLOGY: The Abrahamic covenant, never annulled, reaches its fulfillment in Yeshua, the seed of Abraham, through whom all nations receive blessing (Gal 3:16, 29).',
    },
}